{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5f4030ad-8ff5-401d-8475-6442e07be486","content":"The template is **functional but not fully publish-ready**. Here's what's missing or should be improved:\n\n**Missing fields:**\n- **`$schema`** — Add `\"$schema\": \"http://json.schemastore.org/template\"` for editor validation.\n- **`groupIdentity`** — Required for NuGet so multiple template variants are grouped properly (e.g., `\"MyCompany.WebApi\"`).\n- **`description`** — Important for discoverability on NuGet. Without it, users won't know what the template does.\n\n**Nice-to-have:**\n- **`preferNameDirectory: true`** — Standard for project templates; creates a directory matching the project name.\n- **`precedence`** — Useful if you plan to ship multiple versions.\n\n**Looks good:**\n- `identity`, `name`, `shortName`, `author`, `sourceName` ✅\n- `classifications` and `tags` ✅\n- `Framework` symbol with choices ✅\n\nI'd recommend adding at least `$schema`, `groupIdentity`, and `description` before publishing.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a74f3101-4412-4652-ad60-6c01d0060d7f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me review this template.json for NuGet publishing readiness. I'll check against the .NET template engine schema requirements.\n\nIssues I can identify:\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** — Not required but strongly recommended for validation and editor support.\n2. **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Recommended for NuGet package templates so multiple versions/variants can be grouped.\n3. **Missing `precedence`** — Useful when multiple versions of the same template exist.\n4. **Missing `preferNameDirectory`** — Common for project templates.\n5. **`defaultValue` of `net9.0`** — This is fine, but worth noting the choices are net8.0 and net9.0.\n\n\n6. **`sourceName` replacement** — Set to \"MyWebApi\" which handles namespace replacement appropriately.\n\nBreaking down what's truly essential versus what's nice-to-have, the template has all the required fields lik